    <div class="container">   
      <div  class="jumbotron text-center">
      <h2>Nashville Number System</h2>  
      <!-- PLAY AREA -->    
        <div id="nns"> 
          <h3 style="color:#ffa700" id="tutorial">Tutorial &amp; <a href="#examples" class="btn btn-warning">Examples in Every Key</a> </h3>
          <div>
            <p>A typical number chart may look something like this:  </p>
              <h3>1  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;6- &nbsp;&nbsp;5 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;4 </h3>
              <h3>1 &nbsp;&nbsp;5/7  &nbsp;6- &nbsp;&nbsp;5</h3>  
            <p>Every number is a measure. This particular chart is only 8 measures. </p>
            <p>Dashes indicate minor chords. All other chords are assumed Major. Slashes show that a bass note has been altered.</p>
            <p> If this song IN THE KEY OF C were written using chord symbols it would look like this: </p>
              <h3>C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Am &nbsp;&nbsp;G &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;F </h3>
              <h3>C &nbsp;&nbsp;G/B  &nbsp;Am &nbsp;&nbsp;G</h3> 
            <p>If we changed the above number chart to THE KEY OF D it would look like this: </p>
              <h3>D  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Bm &nbsp;&nbsp;A &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;G </h3>
              <h3>D &nbsp;A/C#  Bm &nbsp;&nbsp;A</h3> 
            <p>We would have had to re-write the chord symbol chart in order to change keys, but the number chart stays the same!
            </p>
          </div>  
        </div> <!-- END PLAY AREA -->  
    </div> <!-- END JUMBOTRON -->
  
  <br>
  
  <div  class="jumbotron text-center" id="examples">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0">Common Number Patterns</h2>
      <p>examples in every key</p>
      <!-- NUMBER PATTERNS -->    
